, Sallust pleasurably combines juicy details about Catiline and his louche associates with highly "able moral judgments and a wrenching description of the widespread social misery they exploited. Along the way, we get unforgettable portraits of the bitter and haunted Catiline, who was sympathetic to the plight of Romans yet willing to destroy Rome; his archenemy Cicero, who thwarts the conspiracy; and Julius Caesar, who defends the conspirators and is accused of being one of them.Complete with an introduction that discusses how The War with Catiline has shaped and continues to shape our understanding of how republics live and die, and featuring the original Latin on facing pages, this volume makes Sallust’s gripping history more accessible than ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAaron Burr.  aAbolitionism.  aAmiternum.  aAntonius.  aAssassination.  aAttempt.  aBehalf.  aBribery.  aCapital punishment.  aCatiline.  aCato the Elder.  aCato the Younger.  aCimbri.  aComplicity.  aConfiscation.  aConspiracy theory.  aCriminal charge.  aCurtailment.  aDeclamation.  aDecree.  aDemagogue.  aDespotism.  aDomitian.  aExplanation.  aFalse accusation.  aFarce.  aFirst Catilinarian conspiracy.  aForay.  aFraud.  aGluttony.  aGordian III.  aGratus.  aHostility.  aIniuria.  aInvidia.  aJugurthine War.  aLegislation.  aLentulus.  aMacedonian Wars.  aMarch on Rome.  aMurder.  aNativism (politics).  aNobility.  aOptimates.  aOxford University Press.  aParody.  aPatrician (ancient Rome).  aPederasty.  aPerjury.  aPlea.  aPolitical philosophy.  aPolitics.  aPolyaenus.  aPompey.  aPraetor.  aPretext.  aProconsul.  aProscription.  aPsychology.  aPunge